1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,000
Hello, everyone, and welcome back to another lesson here at EnglishPod.
大家好，欢迎回到 EnglishPod 的另一节课。

2
00:00:07,000 --> 00:00:08,000
My name is Marco.
我是 Marco。

3
00:00:08,000 --> 00:00:09,480
And my name is Catherine.
我是 Catherine。

4
00:00:09,480 --> 00:00:12,960
And today, Marco, you and I are talking about movies, right?
今天，Marco，你我要聊聊电影，对吧？

5
00:00:12,960 --> 00:00:17,040
We're talking a little bit about movies, but mostly we're having a big argument.
我们聊一点电影，但主要是要大吵一架。

6
00:00:17,040 --> 00:00:19,560
Okay, I kind of like arguments.
好吧，我其实还挺喜欢吵架的。

7
00:00:19,560 --> 00:00:22,700
Lots of great words and phrases for you to learn here in English.
有很多很棒的生词和短语等着你学。

8
00:00:22,700 --> 00:00:26,800
But we've got an upper intermediate level lesson with some people who are not getting
我们有一节中高级课程，讲的是两个人相处得

9
00:00:26,800 --> 00:00:28,240
along very well.
不太好。

10
00:00:28,240 --> 00:00:32,520
It's a couple, a guy and a girl, and they're having a fight, as couples do.
是一对情侣，一男一女，他们在吵架，就像情侣常做的那样。

11
00:00:32,520 --> 00:00:35,580
So we're going to be learning a lot of the different language that they are using in
所以我们会学到很多他们在

12
00:00:35,580 --> 00:00:37,840
this very heated debate.
这场激烈争论中使用的不同语言。

13
00:00:37,840 --> 00:00:44,040
So let's listen to this dialogue for the first time, and then we'll be right back.
我们先听一遍这段对话，然后马上回来。

14
00:00:44,040 --> 00:00:51,920
Wow, that terrible movie is finally over.
哇，那部烂片终于结束了。

15
00:00:51,920 --> 00:00:55,480
Next time I'm picking the film because I don't want to end up seeing a chick flick.
下次我来选电影，我可不想再看什么爱情片了。

16
00:00:55,480 --> 00:00:57,160
Well, you should have picked.
那你刚才就该选啊。

17
00:00:57,160 --> 00:00:59,840
In the end, you always complain about everything.
到头来，你总是抱怨个不停。

18
00:00:59,840 --> 00:01:00,960
Not everything.
不是所有事。

19
00:01:00,960 --> 00:01:02,240
Just this film.
就这部电影。

20
00:01:02,240 --> 00:01:04,200
Even the title was ridiculous.
连片名都那么可笑。

21
00:01:04,200 --> 00:01:05,200
And it's so long.
还那么长。

22
00:01:05,200 --> 00:01:09,680
Those were the two and a half most wasted hours of my life.
那是我生命中最浪费的两个半小时。

23
00:01:09,680 --> 00:01:13,620
So much so that I'm thinking about asking them to give me my money back.
我甚至想找他们退钱。

24
00:01:13,620 --> 00:01:16,080
I'm thinking of taking you back home.
我想带你回家。

25
00:01:16,080 --> 00:01:19,480
I thought we could have a nice evening, but you're always so negative.
我本来以为我们能有个愉快的晚上，但你总是这么消极。

26
00:01:19,480 --> 00:01:24,120
I'm only complaining about a movie that I could have rented or bought and then thrown
我只是在抱怨一部我本来可以租来或买来然后扔进

27
00:01:24,120 --> 00:01:25,120
in the garbage.
垃圾桶的电影。

28
00:01:25,120 --> 00:01:27,360
You see, that's what I'm talking about.
你看，我说的就是这个。

29
00:01:27,360 --> 00:01:30,480
I can't stand your sarcastic jokes anymore.
我再也受不了你的讽刺笑话了。

30
00:01:30,480 --> 00:01:33,520
Next time, go with your gay friend who is more in touch with his feelings.
下次，跟你那个更懂感情的娘娘腔朋友去吧。

31
00:01:33,520 --> 00:01:35,520
Well, he's more of a man than you are.
哼，他比你更有男人味。

32
00:01:35,520 --> 00:01:38,360
At least he appreciates love stories.
至少他懂得欣赏爱情故事。

33
00:01:38,360 --> 00:01:39,440
Love stories?
爱情故事？

34
00:01:39,440 --> 00:01:41,520
More like one night stands.
更像是一夜情吧。

35
00:01:41,520 --> 00:01:45,880
Don't criticize Mario, or else I'll start on those fat, drunk friends of yours.
别说 Mario，不然我就开始说你那些又胖又醉的朋友。

36
00:01:45,880 --> 00:01:46,920
They're no saints.
他们可不是什么圣人。

37
00:01:46,920 --> 00:01:47,920
My friends?
我朋友？

38
00:01:47,920 --> 00:01:48,920
Fat?
胖？

39
00:01:48,920 --> 00:01:51,160
What about those whales you call friends?
那你那些鲸鱼朋友呢？

40
00:01:51,160 --> 00:01:52,320
You're unbearable.
你真让人受不了。

41
00:01:52,320 --> 00:01:53,320
You can walk home.
你自己走回家吧。

42
00:01:53,320 --> 00:01:54,320
I'm leaving.
我走了。

43
00:01:54,320 --> 00:02:07,720
I think the guy was exaggerating a little bit.
我觉得那男的有点夸张了。

44
00:02:07,720 --> 00:02:08,720
What do you think?
你觉得呢？

45
00:02:08,720 --> 00:02:09,720
I think they were both exaggerating.
我觉得他们俩都夸张了。

46
00:02:09,720 --> 00:02:14,320
You know, by the end of an argument, both people are saying things that maybe they don't
你知道，吵架到最后，两个人都会说一些可能不是

47
00:02:14,320 --> 00:02:15,320
mean.
真心的气话。

48
00:02:15,320 --> 00:02:18,920
I think we'll talk a little bit more about this towards the end of the show, but now,
我们会在节目结尾再聊这个，但现在，

49
00:02:18,920 --> 00:02:23,160
why don't we take a look at language takeaway.
我们先来看看语言要点。

50
00:02:23,160 --> 00:02:25,320
Language takeaway.
语言要点。

51
00:02:25,320 --> 00:02:29,120
Alright on language takeaway today, we have four words and the first one that you probably
好的，今天的语言要点，我们有四个词，第一个你大概

52
00:02:29,120 --> 00:02:32,960
saw in the very first sentence is a chick flick.
在第一句话里就看到了：chick flick。

53
00:02:32,960 --> 00:02:33,960
Chick flick.
Chick flick。

54
00:02:33,960 --> 00:02:36,560
So, first of all, the word chick means a woman.
首先，chick 这个词指女人。

55
00:02:36,560 --> 00:02:38,520
It's slang and it's not very nice.
是俚语，不太礼貌。

56
00:02:38,520 --> 00:02:39,520
It's not very nice.
不太礼貌。

57
00:02:39,520 --> 00:02:40,520
No.
对。

58
00:02:40,520 --> 00:02:44,240
Well, I mean, between guys, you would use it as like, oh, this chick or that chick,
嗯，我的意思是，男人之间会用，比如“这个 chick”或“那个 chick”，

59
00:02:44,240 --> 00:02:46,880
but you wouldn't really walk up to a girl and call her a chick, right?
但你不会直接走到一个女孩面前叫她 chick，对吧？

60
00:02:46,880 --> 00:02:50,200
No, you wouldn't say, hey, chick, what's up?
对，你不会说“嘿，chick，咋样？”

61
00:02:50,200 --> 00:02:51,360
Not something you want to say.
这不是你想说的话。

62
00:02:51,360 --> 00:02:57,280
So chick is a slang word for a girl or a woman and a chick flick is a girl's movie.
所以 chick 是女孩或女人的俚语，chick flick 就是女孩看的电影。

63
00:02:57,280 --> 00:02:59,080
So a flick is a movie.
所以 flick 是电影。

64
00:02:59,080 --> 00:03:00,080
Another slang word.
另一个俚语。

65
00:03:00,080 --> 00:03:01,080
Exactly.
没错。

66
00:03:01,080 --> 00:03:03,080
So this is the slang phrase for flick.
所以这是 flick 的俚语说法。

67
00:03:03,080 --> 00:03:06,120
So hey, Marco, what flicks are showing at the movie theater?
所以，嘿，Marco，电影院在放什么 flicks？

68
00:03:06,120 --> 00:03:07,120
All right.
好的。

69
00:03:07,120 --> 00:03:08,120
Yeah.
嗯。

70
00:03:08,120 --> 00:03:09,120
So movies.
就是电影。

71
00:03:09,120 --> 00:03:14,200
So in the chick flick is usually a romantic movie, a drama, something that's very, um.
所以 chick flick 通常是指浪漫电影、剧情片，那种很……

72
00:03:14,200 --> 00:03:15,200
Like beaches.
比如《海滩》。

73
00:03:15,200 --> 00:03:17,080
Beaches is a chick flick.
《海滩》就是一部 chick flick。

74
00:03:17,080 --> 00:03:18,400
I don't know if you've ever seen that.
不知道你看过没有。

75
00:03:18,400 --> 00:03:19,400
I've never seen it.
我没看过。

76
00:03:19,400 --> 00:03:22,880
So he's just not that into you is one of those new chick flicks.
所以《他其实没那么喜欢你》是那种新的 chick flick。

77
00:03:22,880 --> 00:03:25,280
Or like how to lose a guy in 10 days.
或者像《十天丢个郎》。

78
00:03:25,280 --> 00:03:26,280
Yeah.
嗯。

79
00:03:26,280 --> 00:03:29,120
How to lose a guy in 10 days or the devil wears Prada.
《十天丢个郎》或《穿普拉达的女王》。

80
00:03:29,120 --> 00:03:30,120
Bride Wars.
《新娘大作战》。

81
00:03:30,120 --> 00:03:31,120
Bride Wars.
《新娘大作战》。

82
00:03:31,120 --> 00:03:32,120
Wow.
哇。

83
00:03:32,120 --> 00:03:33,120
Lots of chick flicks.
好多 chick flick。

84
00:03:33,120 --> 00:03:35,320
I've actually never seen any one of these except how to lose a guy in 10 days.
其实这些我一部都没看过，除了《十天丢个郎》。

85
00:03:35,320 --> 00:03:36,880
I've actually only seen that one.
我只看了那一部。

86
00:03:36,880 --> 00:03:37,880
All right.
好的。

87
00:03:37,880 --> 00:03:41,480
So chick flick is a girl's or woman's movie.
所以 chick flick 就是女孩或女人看的电影。

88
00:03:41,480 --> 00:03:44,240
And next up we have a word, sarcastic.
下一个词是 sarcastic。

89
00:03:44,240 --> 00:03:46,040
We're talking about sarcastic jokes.
我们说的是 sarcastic jokes。

90
00:03:46,040 --> 00:03:48,960
So sarcastic jokes or somebody being sarcastic.
所以是讽刺的笑话，或者某人很 sarcastic。

91
00:03:48,960 --> 00:03:51,240
God, Marco, you're always so sarcastic.
天哪，Marco，你总是这么 sarcastic。

92
00:03:51,240 --> 00:03:53,760
So what would sarcasm sound like?
那讽刺听起来是什么样？

93
00:03:53,760 --> 00:03:56,920
Um, yeah, he's really funny.
嗯，他真有趣。

94
00:03:56,920 --> 00:03:58,440
All right.
好的。

95
00:03:58,440 --> 00:04:00,380
So it's not really what you're saying.
所以关键不在于你说什么。

96
00:04:00,380 --> 00:04:02,320
It's kind of how you're saying it.
而在于你怎么说。

97
00:04:02,320 --> 00:04:03,320
Right.
对。

98
00:04:03,320 --> 00:04:06,480
So it's kind of like by saying, he's really funny.
所以就像说“他真有趣”。

99
00:04:06,480 --> 00:04:07,720
You're saying, yeah, he's a funny guy.
你是在说“嗯，他是个有趣的人”。

100
00:04:07,720 --> 00:04:10,520
But if I say, oh, he's really funny.
但如果我说“哦，他真有趣”。

101
00:04:10,520 --> 00:04:13,040
I'm saying he's not funny.
我其实是在说“他一点都不有趣”。

102
00:04:13,040 --> 00:04:15,840
He's being mean or he's a jerk.
他刻薄或者是个混蛋。

103
00:04:15,840 --> 00:04:20,160
Sarcasm is kind of one of those things that it's a little bit difficult to learn how to
讽刺是那种有点难学会

104
00:04:20,160 --> 00:04:22,760
do or to actually get it right.
或掌握好的东西。

105
00:04:22,760 --> 00:04:23,760
Especially in English.
尤其是在英语里。

106
00:04:23,760 --> 00:04:24,760
Right?
对吧？

107
00:04:24,760 --> 00:04:25,760
Yeah.
嗯。

108
00:04:25,760 --> 00:04:26,760
Marco, great explanation.
Marco，解释得真好。

109
00:04:26,760 --> 00:04:27,760
Exactly.
没错。

110
00:04:27,760 --> 00:04:28,760
That's the way it goes.
就是这样。

111
00:04:28,760 --> 00:04:29,760
Oh, yeah.
哦，是啊。

112
00:04:29,760 --> 00:04:30,760
You're so funny.
你真有趣。

113
00:04:30,760 --> 00:04:31,760
So you're amazing.
你真了不起。

114
00:04:31,760 --> 00:04:32,760
You should go to you.
你应该去……

115
00:04:32,760 --> 00:04:33,760
You went to sarcasm school.
你上过讽刺学校吧。

116
00:04:33,760 --> 00:04:34,760
So my parents like to say.
我爸妈常这么说。

117
00:04:34,760 --> 00:04:35,760
You can be really mean, Catherine.
你可以很刻薄，Catherine。

118
00:04:35,760 --> 00:04:36,760
Sorry.
抱歉。

119
00:04:36,760 --> 00:04:37,760
Just kidding.
开玩笑的。

120
00:04:37,760 --> 00:04:38,760
All right.
好的。

121
00:04:38,760 --> 00:04:43,600
So apart from being sarcastic, you can criticize someone.
除了讽刺之外，你还可以批评别人。

122
00:04:43,600 --> 00:04:44,600
Like you're ever critical.
说得好像你经常批评人似的。

123
00:04:44,600 --> 00:04:45,880
All right.
好吧。

124
00:04:45,880 --> 00:04:47,880
Sorry, I'll stop.
抱歉，我不说了。

125
00:04:47,880 --> 00:04:49,480
You're really into character right now.
你现在真是入戏太深了。

126
00:04:49,480 --> 00:04:50,480
All right.
好吧。

127
00:04:50,480 --> 00:04:55,680
So critical to criticize someone is to complain about them or to say that the things that
所以，“批评”某人就是抱怨他们，或者说他们做的事情

128
00:04:55,680 --> 00:04:57,880
they do are not very good.
不太好。

129
00:04:57,880 --> 00:05:00,080
So you can criticize a person or a movie.
所以你可以批评一个人或一部电影。

130
00:05:00,080 --> 00:05:01,080
Yeah.
是的。

131
00:05:01,080 --> 00:05:02,520
So this movie wasn't very good.
所以这部电影不怎么样。

132
00:05:02,520 --> 00:05:03,520
It wasn't funny.
它不好笑。

133
00:05:03,520 --> 00:05:04,600
The actors were bad.
演员也很差。

134
00:05:04,600 --> 00:05:06,280
It was really long.
它太长了。

135
00:05:06,280 --> 00:05:07,280
These are criticisms.
这些都是批评。

136
00:05:07,280 --> 00:05:08,280
Criticisms.
批评。

137
00:05:08,280 --> 00:05:09,280
All right.
好吧。

138
00:05:09,280 --> 00:05:13,080
Well, and then moving on, the girl was finally tired of the guy and his complaints.
嗯，接着往下，女孩终于受够了那个男人和他的抱怨。

139
00:05:13,080 --> 00:05:15,120
And she said he's unbearable.
她说他让人受不了。

140
00:05:15,120 --> 00:05:17,680
Gosh, you're unbearable.
天哪，你真让人受不了。

141
00:05:17,680 --> 00:05:22,800
So the root of this word is to be able to like to stand something, to bear it.
所以这个词的词根是“能够忍受”或“承受”某事。

142
00:05:22,800 --> 00:05:27,680
And so if you're unbearable, something is unbearable, you just can't stand it.
所以如果你让人受不了，或者某事让人受不了，就是你无法忍受。

143
00:05:27,680 --> 00:05:28,680
All right.
好吧。

144
00:05:28,680 --> 00:05:29,680
So you're tired of it.
所以你厌烦了。

145
00:05:29,680 --> 00:05:30,680
You can't stand it.
你受不了了。

146
00:05:30,680 --> 00:05:34,240
She thinks he's so unbearable, she makes him get out of the car.
她觉得他太让人受不了了，就让他下车。

147
00:05:34,240 --> 00:05:35,240
And she leaves.
然后她走了。

148
00:05:35,240 --> 00:05:36,240
Yeah.
是的。

149
00:05:36,240 --> 00:05:37,240
She said you can walk home.
她说你可以走回家。

150
00:05:37,240 --> 00:05:38,240
All right.
好吧。

151
00:05:38,240 --> 00:05:40,480
So that's an unbearable person, right?
所以这就是一个让人受不了的人，对吧？

152
00:05:40,480 --> 00:05:41,480
Okay.
好的。

153
00:05:41,480 --> 00:05:46,440
So we took a look at those four main words here in our dialogue.
所以我们看了对话中的这四个主要词汇。

154
00:05:46,440 --> 00:05:52,000
Let's move on now to some of the phrases that we found in Fluency Builder.
现在我们来看看“流利度构建”中的一些短语。

155
00:05:52,000 --> 00:05:53,760
Fluency Builder.
流利度构建。

156
00:05:53,760 --> 00:05:59,080
This first one's a common one, especially when we talk about women and men and the relationship
第一个很常见，尤其是当我们谈论男女以及

157
00:05:59,080 --> 00:06:00,080
between women and men.
男女之间的关系时。

158
00:06:00,080 --> 00:06:05,280
We say about men that maybe they should be more in touch with their feelings or their
我们常说男人也许应该更关注自己的感受或

159
00:06:05,280 --> 00:06:06,280
feminine side.
女性化的一面。

160
00:06:06,280 --> 00:06:07,280
Yeah.
是的。

161
00:06:07,280 --> 00:06:13,000
Okay, so if you're saying to be more in touch with your feminine side, what exactly are
好的，所以如果你说“更关注你的女性化一面”，你到底在

162
00:06:13,000 --> 00:06:14,000
you saying?
说什么？

163
00:06:14,000 --> 00:06:15,000
It's a good question.
这是个好问题。

164
00:06:15,000 --> 00:06:19,040
Well, what you're saying is that you want to be able to express your feelings more or
嗯，你的意思是希望自己能更多地表达感受，或者

165
00:06:19,040 --> 00:06:25,280
you want to be able to understand more about your feminine side or something like this.
希望更了解自己的女性化一面之类的。

166
00:06:25,280 --> 00:06:28,460
So to be in touch with is more about yourself.
所以“关注”更多是关于自己。

167
00:06:28,460 --> 00:06:32,120
It's about self-reflection and self-understanding.
是关于自我反思和自我理解。

168
00:06:32,120 --> 00:06:36,280
So you could say, I'm a very serious person, but I want to make some changes in my life.
所以你可以说，我是个很严肃的人，但我想在生活中做些改变。

169
00:06:36,280 --> 00:06:39,320
So I'm trying to be more in touch with my inner child.
所以我试着更关注自己的童心。

170
00:06:39,320 --> 00:06:40,320
Your inner child.
你的童心。

171
00:06:40,320 --> 00:06:41,320
All right.
好吧。

172
00:06:41,320 --> 00:06:47,480
So to be in touch with, and it's usually related to feelings, to something intangible.
所以“关注”通常与感受、无形的东西有关。

173
00:06:47,480 --> 00:06:48,480
Or to behavior.
或者与行为有关。

174
00:06:48,480 --> 00:06:49,480
To behavior.
与行为有关。

175
00:06:49,480 --> 00:06:50,920
All right.
好吧。

176
00:06:50,920 --> 00:06:54,840
Moving on now, a heated phrase, a one night stand.
接下来，一个热辣的短语：“一夜情”。

177
00:06:54,840 --> 00:06:57,480
Oh, I'll let you explain this one, Marco.
哦，这个让马可来解释吧。

178
00:06:57,480 --> 00:06:58,480
All right.
好吧。

179
00:06:58,480 --> 00:07:05,040
So a one night stand is a casual and very quick temporal encounter that's usually a
所以“一夜情”是一种随意的、非常短暂的临时相遇，通常

180
00:07:05,040 --> 00:07:06,360
sexual encounter.
是性方面的相遇。

181
00:07:06,360 --> 00:07:07,360
It's romantic, right?
是浪漫的，对吧？

182
00:07:07,360 --> 00:07:10,680
So it can be between two different people.
所以可以发生在两个人之间。

183
00:07:10,680 --> 00:07:12,960
They meet each other one night.
他们某晚相遇。

184
00:07:12,960 --> 00:07:17,280
They have a relationship for one night only, and then they never see each other again.
他们只维持一晚的关系，然后再也不见。

185
00:07:17,280 --> 00:07:18,280
So it's casual.
所以很随意。

186
00:07:18,280 --> 00:07:19,280
It's casual.
很随意。

187
00:07:19,280 --> 00:07:20,760
Very good.
非常好。

188
00:07:20,760 --> 00:07:22,000
So yeah, you would see this.
所以是的，你会看到这个。

189
00:07:22,000 --> 00:07:25,280
You see this a lot in shows like, you know, Sex in the City and all that stuff.
你在像《欲望都市》之类的剧里经常看到。

190
00:07:25,280 --> 00:07:28,080
Yeah, they have a lot of one night stands in that show.
是的，那部剧里有很多一夜情。

191
00:07:28,080 --> 00:07:29,080
All right.
好吧。

192
00:07:29,080 --> 00:07:30,960
So a one night stand.
所以“一夜情”。

193
00:07:30,960 --> 00:07:37,240
And well, related to this, the girl was criticizing his friends, and she said, they're no saints.
嗯，与此相关，女孩在批评他的朋友，她说他们不是圣人。

194
00:07:37,240 --> 00:07:38,240
Okay.
好的。

195
00:07:38,240 --> 00:07:39,840
So we can say this in many different ways.
所以我们可以用很多不同的方式说这个。

196
00:07:39,840 --> 00:07:41,000
He's no saint.
他不是圣人。

197
00:07:41,000 --> 00:07:42,000
She's no saint.
她不是圣人。

198
00:07:42,000 --> 00:07:43,000
Or I'm no saint.
或者我不是圣人。

199
00:07:43,000 --> 00:07:44,000
You're no saint.
你不是圣人。

200
00:07:44,000 --> 00:07:45,320
So a saint is a good person.
所以“圣人”是个好人。

201
00:07:45,320 --> 00:07:51,000
It's a word that we use in religion to say someone who's like Mother Teresa, or someone
这是一个宗教用语，指像特蕾莎修女那样的人，或者

202
00:07:51,000 --> 00:07:52,960
who's just really good and kind.
非常善良、仁慈的人。

203
00:07:52,960 --> 00:07:54,200
Doesn't commit any sins.
不犯任何罪。

204
00:07:54,200 --> 00:07:55,200
Exactly.
没错。

205
00:07:55,200 --> 00:07:58,760
And so to say, I'm no saint is to say, well, I do bad things, or I say bad things.
所以说“我不是圣人”就是承认，嗯，我做坏事，或者说坏话。

206
00:07:58,760 --> 00:07:59,760
I'm not perfect.
我不完美。

207
00:07:59,760 --> 00:08:00,760
Okay.
好的。

208
00:08:00,760 --> 00:08:02,800
So he or they, they're no saints.
所以他或他们，他们不是圣人。

209
00:08:02,800 --> 00:08:04,000
They do bad stuff too.
他们也做坏事。

210
00:08:04,000 --> 00:08:05,000
Yeah, very good.
是的，非常好。

211
00:08:05,000 --> 00:08:08,880
So that's the way that you would use, he's no saint, they're no saints.
所以这就是你使用“他不是圣人”、“他们不是圣人”的方式。

212
00:08:08,880 --> 00:08:09,880
All right.
好吧。

213
00:08:09,880 --> 00:08:15,800
So I think now we should listen to our dialogue for the last time, and we'll be right back.
所以我想现在我们该最后一次听对话了，我们马上回来。

214
00:08:15,800 --> 00:08:24,760
Wow, that terrible movie is finally over.
哇，那部烂片终于结束了。

215
00:08:24,760 --> 00:08:28,320
Next time I'm picking the film because I don't want to end up seeing a chick flick.
下次我来选电影，因为我不想再看爱情片了。

216
00:08:28,320 --> 00:08:30,000
Well, you should have picked.
嗯，你当时就该选。

217
00:08:30,000 --> 00:08:32,720
In the end, you always complain about everything.
到头来，你总是抱怨一切。

218
00:08:32,720 --> 00:08:35,120
Not everything, just this film.
不是一切，只是这部电影。

219
00:08:35,120 --> 00:08:37,080
Even the title was ridiculous.
连片名都很荒谬。

220
00:08:37,080 --> 00:08:38,080
And it's so long.
而且它太长了。

221
00:08:38,080 --> 00:08:42,520
Those were the two and a half most wasted hours of my life.
那是我生命中最浪费的两个半小时。

222
00:08:42,520 --> 00:08:46,480
So much so that I'm thinking about asking them to give me my money back.
以至于我在想让他们退我钱。

223
00:08:46,480 --> 00:08:48,960
I'm thinking of taking you back home.
我在想把你送回家。

224
00:08:48,960 --> 00:08:52,360
I thought we could have a nice evening, but you're always so negative.
我本以为我们能有个愉快的夜晚，但你总是这么消极。

225
00:08:52,360 --> 00:08:57,000
I'm only complaining about a movie that I could have rented or bought and then thrown
我只是在抱怨一部我本可以租或买来然后扔进

226
00:08:57,000 --> 00:08:58,000
in the garbage.
垃圾桶的电影。

227
00:08:58,000 --> 00:09:00,200
You see, that's what I'm talking about.
你看，这就是我说的。

228
00:09:00,200 --> 00:09:03,320
I can't stand your sarcastic jokes anymore.
我再也受不了你的讽刺笑话了。

229
00:09:03,320 --> 00:09:06,400
Next time, go with your gay friend who's more in touch with his feelings.
下次，跟你那个更关注自己感受的同志朋友去吧。

230
00:09:06,400 --> 00:09:08,720
Well, he's more of a man than you are.
嗯，他比你更像个男人。

231
00:09:08,720 --> 00:09:11,200
At least he appreciates love stories.
至少他欣赏爱情故事。

232
00:09:11,200 --> 00:09:12,280
Love stories?
爱情故事？

233
00:09:12,280 --> 00:09:14,360
More like one night stands.
更像是“一夜情”。

234
00:09:14,360 --> 00:09:18,760
Don't criticize Mario, or else I'll start on those fat drunk friends of yours.
别批评马里奥，否则我就开始说你那些胖醉鬼朋友了。

235
00:09:18,760 --> 00:09:19,760
They're no saints.
他们也不是圣人。

236
00:09:19,760 --> 00:09:20,760
My friends?
我的朋友？

237
00:09:20,760 --> 00:09:21,760
Fat?
胖？

238
00:09:21,760 --> 00:09:24,040
What about those whales you call friends?
那你那些叫“鲸鱼”的朋友呢？

239
00:09:24,040 --> 00:09:25,160
You're unbearable.
你真让人受不了。

240
00:09:25,160 --> 00:09:26,160
You can walk home.
你走回家吧。

241
00:09:26,160 --> 00:09:27,160
I'm leaving.
我要走了。

242
00:09:27,160 --> 00:09:28,160
Bye.
再见。

243
00:09:28,160 --> 00:09:29,160
Good luck.
祝你好运。

244
00:09:29,160 --> 00:09:30,160
Bye.
再见。

245
00:09:30,160 --> 00:09:45,720
All right, so, Catherine, is this an argument that you would say is typical among couples?
好的，那么，凯瑟琳，你觉得这是情侣间典型的争吵吗？

246
00:09:45,720 --> 00:09:49,420
Or maybe people that are probably about to break up?
还是说可能是快要分手的人之间才会有的？

247
00:09:49,420 --> 00:09:51,440
Not couples that are happy, I would say.
我觉得不是幸福的情侣会有的。

248
00:09:51,440 --> 00:09:54,240
But yeah, you definitely have people who are...
但确实，有些人会这样……

249
00:09:54,240 --> 00:09:56,840
Well, I guess it's kind of the battle of the sexes, right?
嗯，我想这有点像两性之间的较量，对吧？

250
00:09:56,840 --> 00:10:01,420
You have people who are different genders and so they don't always understand each other.
不同性别的人，所以不一定总能理解对方。

251
00:10:01,420 --> 00:10:04,560
You know, you want to have your girlfriends as a girl and your girlfriends behave and
你知道，作为女生，你想和闺蜜在一起，而闺蜜们会以某种方式相处和

252
00:10:04,560 --> 00:10:08,660
talk in a certain way together and guys do the same thing but with their friends.
聊天，男生们也一样，但和他们的朋友在一起时。

253
00:10:08,660 --> 00:10:13,080
And so sometimes you have these clashes, these interactions that are negative and you know
所以有时候会有这些冲突，这些负面的互动，而且你知道

254
00:10:13,080 --> 00:10:16,120
when people are upset with each other, they say mean things.
当人们彼此生气时，他们会说刻薄的话。

255
00:10:16,120 --> 00:10:19,560
And especially I think in this case, they don't really like each other's friends.
特别是这次，我觉得他们真的不喜欢对方的朋友。

256
00:10:19,560 --> 00:10:20,560
Exactly.
没错。

257
00:10:20,560 --> 00:10:22,440
And that's a kind of a common thing.
这还挺常见的。

258
00:10:22,440 --> 00:10:28,600
Like a guy doesn't like his girlfriend's friends because maybe they gossip too much or something
比如，男生不喜欢女朋友的朋友，可能是因为她们太爱八卦或什么的。

259
00:10:28,600 --> 00:10:29,600
like that.
类似这样。

260
00:10:29,600 --> 00:10:30,600
And the same thing with the girls, right?
女生也一样，对吧？

261
00:10:30,600 --> 00:10:32,720
Because a guy's friends maybe drink too much.
因为男生的朋友可能喝太多酒了。

262
00:10:32,720 --> 00:10:34,760
Drink too much, play too many card games.
喝太多酒，玩太多牌。

263
00:10:34,760 --> 00:10:35,760
They're single.
他们都是单身。

264
00:10:35,760 --> 00:10:40,360
So I think a lot of times these problems also have to do with the fact that like when a
所以我觉得很多时候这些问题也跟这个事实有关：当一个

265
00:10:40,360 --> 00:10:43,000
girl is with her girlfriend, she maybe acts differently.
女生和她的闺蜜在一起时，她可能表现得不一样。

266
00:10:43,000 --> 00:10:44,840
Or when a guy is with his guy friends.
或者当一个男生和他的哥们在一起时。

267
00:10:44,840 --> 00:10:50,040
And so that's weird sometimes for the relationship because you see your partner acting differently
所以这对关系来说有时很奇怪，因为你看到你的伴侣和别人在一起时表现不同。

268
00:10:50,040 --> 00:10:51,040
with other people.
和别人在一起时。

269
00:10:51,040 --> 00:10:52,040
Right.
对。

270
00:10:52,040 --> 00:10:53,520
So, do you like your boyfriend or girlfriend's friends?
那么，你喜欢你男朋友或女朋友的朋友吗？

271
00:10:53,520 --> 00:10:55,400
Do you get in fights about this kind of stuff?
你们会为这种事吵架吗？

272
00:10:55,400 --> 00:10:56,400
Or you know what?
或者你知道吗？

273
00:10:56,400 --> 00:10:57,400
The in-laws.
还有姻亲。

274
00:10:57,400 --> 00:10:59,680
Oh, that's a whole another situation.
哦，那完全是另一回事了。

275
00:10:59,680 --> 00:11:01,680
That's a whole another situation.
那完全是另一回事了。

276
00:11:01,680 --> 00:11:02,680
Absolutely.
绝对是的。

277
00:11:02,680 --> 00:11:07,240
Alright, so we want to hear from you and also if you have any questions or comment suggestions,
好了，所以我们想听听你的意见，如果你有任何问题或评论建议，

278
00:11:07,240 --> 00:11:11,560
come to EnglishPod.com and you can leave it on our lessons page or you can email us at
请访问EnglishPod.com，你可以留在我们的课程页面上，或者发邮件到

279
